content:
Calculate the energy and wavelength associated with an $\alpha$ particle that has fallen through a potential difference of $4.0 \mathrm{~V}$. Take the mass of an $\alpha$ particle to be $6.64 \times 10^{-27} \mathrm{~kg}$. The unit of the answer should be  $
\text { 1-41. } 1.3 \times 10^{-18} \mathrm{~J} / \alpha \text {-particle, }
$.

$$
\text { If we locate an electron to within } 20 \mathrm{pm} \text {, then what is the uncertainty in its speed? }
$$ The unit of the answer should be $10^7 \mathrm{~m} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-1}$ .

The power output of a laser is measured in units of watts (W), where one watt is equal to one joule per second. $\left(1 \mathrm{~W}=1 \mathrm{~J} \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-1}\right.$.) What is the number of photons emitted per second by a $1.00 \mathrm{~mW}$ nitrogen laser? The wavelength emitted by a nitrogen laser is $337 \mathrm{~nm}$. The unit of the answer should be  $
10^{15} \text { photon } \cdot \mathrm{s}^{-1}
$.
